{{Infobox person |name = Louisa Bojesen |image = Louisa Bojesen - 2010 WEF Middle East (1).jpg |image_size = 200 |caption = Bojesen moderates a debate at the 2010 [[World Economic Forum]] on the Middle East in [[Morocco]]. |birth_place = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] |occupation = Business Journalist |employer = [[CNBC]] (2000-2017) |spouse = |children = }}
'''Louisa Bojesen''' ({{IPA-da|luˈiːsa ˈbʌjəsn̩}}) (born May 13, 1974) is a [[Denmark|Danish]]-[[United States|American]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dr.dk/Nyheder/Penge/Jobliv/2008/03/14/105238.htm|title=Topleder - vis dit sande ansigt!|date=14 March 2008|work=[[DR (broadcaster)|DR]]|language=Danish|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref> financial journalist who worked for [[CNBC Europe]] television in London for 17 years. She was most recently a co-host of the channel's European version of ''[[Street Signs (TV series)|Street Signs]]'', reporting on global financial markets. In addition, Bojesen reported for [[CNBC|CNBC (U.S.)]], [[CNBC Asia]], [[NBC]] and [[MSNBC]]. She co-anchored ''[[Squawk Box Europe]]'' with [[Geoff Cutmore]] and [[Steve Sedgwick]] and anchored ''[[European Closing Bell]]'' until its final show on December 18, 2015. Bojesen co-anchored the European version of ''Street Signs'' until her departure from CNBC Europe on April 28, 2017.
Bojesen studied [[political science]], [[medicine]] and [[philosophy]] at [[Loyola University Chicago]] before working as a [[trader (finance)|trader]].<ref name="BT">{{cite news|url=http://www.business.dk/bny/kridt-skoene-og-vis-ansigt|title=Kridt skoene og vis ansigt|last=Horn|first=Peter|date=13 March 2008|newspaper=[[Berlingske Tidende]]|language=Danish|accessdate=13 October 2010}}</ref> She joined CNBC Europe in 2000, initially serving as a Nordic markets reporter in [[Copenhagen]] before moving to the channel's London headquarters.<ref name="BT" />
In addition to her long-running duties on ''Squawk Box Europe'', Bojesen was also formerly the host of CNBC's ''[[Power Lunch Europe]]'' between 2005 and its cancellation in early 2009. From 1999 through 2008, she served as the morning financial reporter for NBC's ''[[Early Today]]''.
In 2008 she filmed the [[documentary]] ''Outbound Africa'' for CNBC, exploring the [[climate change|impact of the environment]] and [[poverty]] on rural [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/29298865|title=Outbound Africa with Richard Harvey|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> Bojesen made a brief appearance as herself in the 2005 [[BBC]] [[TV movie]] ''[[The Girl in the Café]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.msn.com/movies/movie-cast-and-crew/the-girl-in-the-caf%C3%A9/|title=The Girl in the Café : Cast & Crew|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref>
Bojesen was regularly seen on MSNBC's ''[[Morning Joe]]'' and (now cancelled) ''[[Way Too Early]]'', providing early snapshots of the various U.S. and overseas markets.
Bojesen has covered such events as the [[Mobile World Congress]] and the [[World Economic Forum]]'s annual [[Middle East]] meeting for CNBC. She has hosted the GSM Awards Ceremony in Cannes as well, the Pan European IR Awards in Zurich in October 2006 and was a speaker at the Danish Media Festival in November 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fagfestival.dk/sw2191.asp|title=2006 > Oplægsholdere > Louisa Bojesen|publisher=Fagfestival (Danish Media Festival)|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref> She hosted the Pan European IR Awards in Vienna in 2005, as well as the 2006 Nordic IR Awards in Stockholm. She has also given presentations on the Nordic economy at the [[London Stock Exchange]].<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/15838770 CNBC Europe]</ref>
