'''''Still Got the Blues''''' is the eighth solo [[studio album]] by Northern [[Irish people|Irish]] [[guitarist]] [[Gary Moore]], released in 1990. It marked a substantial change in style for Moore, who, prior to this album, was predominantly known for [[Rock music|rock]] and [[hard rock]] music with [[Skid Row (blues-rock band)|Skid Row]], [[Thin Lizzy]], [[G-Force (Gary Moore album)|G-Force]], [[Greg Lake]] and during his own extensive solo career, as well as his [[jazz-fusion]] work with [[Colosseum II]]. As evidenced by its title, ''Still Got the Blues'' saw him delve into an [[electric blues]] style.
The album features guest contributions from [[Albert King]], [[Albert Collins]] and [[George Harrison]].
The title track was released as a single and reached No. 97 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on 16 February 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=gary moore|chart=Hot 100}}|title=Gary Moore - Chart History|publisher=Crapfromthepast.com|accessdate=2013-07-26}}</ref> To date, it is the only single of Moore's to chart on the Billboard Hot 100.
The album reached No. 83 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] on 16 February 1991, then was certified [[Music recording sales certification|gold]] by the [[RIAA]] on November 1995. This was the most successful album both in sales and chart positions from Gary Moore in the US.
