{{Infobox Painting | image_file=File:Edgar Degas The Dance Class.jpg | image_size =200px | title=The Dance Class | artist=[[Edgar Degas]] | year=1874 | type=[[Oil paint]] on [[canvas]] | dimensions = {{convert|83.5|x|77.2|cm|in}} | city=[[New York City]] | museum=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] | accession=1987.47.1 }}
'''''The Dance Class''''' is an 1874 painting by [[Edgar Degas]].<ref name="The New York Times - 2 September 2008 - Degas's Ballet Students Teach the Lessons of Their Art">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/03/arts/dance/03dega.html?pagewanted=all|title=Degas's Ballet Students Teach the Lessons of Their Art|last=[[Alastair Macaulay]]|date=September 2, 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> It is in the collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref name="Metropolitan Museum of Art - The Collection Online - The Dance Class - Edgar Degas">{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/438817?=&imgNo=0&tabName=object-information|title=The Collection Online - The Dance Class - Edgar Degas|publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>
The painting and its companion work in the [[Musée d'Orsay]], Paris are amongst the most ambitious works by Degas on the theme of ballet. The imaginary scene depicts a dance class being held under the supervision of [[Jules Perrot]], a famous ballet master, in the old Paris Opera, which had actually burnt down the previous year. The poster on the wall for [[Gioachino Rossini|Rossini]]’s [[William Tell (opera)|Guillaume Tell]] is a tribute to the operatic singer [[Jean-Baptiste Faure]], who had commissioned the work.
The picture is on view in the Met Museum's Gallery 815.
